---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Velocity anisotropy (β parameter)";
import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Velocity anisotropy (β parameter)</h1>

    <p>
      The <strong>velocity anisotropy parameter β</strong> quantifies the ratio of tangential to radial velocity dispersion in a stellar population. It is defined as:
    </p>
    <p style="text-align: center;">
      β = 1 − (σ_θ² + σ_φ²) / (2σ_r²)
    </p>
    <p>where σ_i is the velocity dispersion in the i-th direction.</p>

    <h2>Physical interpretation</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>β = 0:</strong> Isotropic velocity distribution (equal dispersion in all directions)</li>
      <li><strong>0 &lt; β &lt; 1:</strong> Mixed radial and tangential motions (typical of mergers and accreted components)</li>
      <li><strong>β → 1:</strong> Purely radial orbits (high eccentricity, e ≳ 0.95)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Dynamical importance</h2>
    <p>
      The anisotropy parameter strongly affects how stellar populations respond to gravitational perturbations. Dillamore et al. (2026) show that high-β (β ≈ 0.9) components like the GSE undergo more dramatic reshaping and tilt in response to the LMC's tidal field, with characteristic alignment timescales of ~1 Gyr<sup><a href="/pages/dillamore_2026_gse_lmc">1</a></sup>.
    </p>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Dillamore A. M., Sanders J. L., Brooks R. A. N. (2026). arXiv:2603.11159.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
